isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.58) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.27. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.28, p < .001, 95% CI [12.98, 14.08]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.40, p = 0.747, 95% CI [-0.91, 0.65]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.20, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.46, S.E. = 0.33, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.09, -1.82]; Std. beta = -0.55, 95% CI [-0.70, -0.41])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.12, S.E. = 0.40, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.90, -2.33]; Std. beta = -0.70, 95% CI [-0.88, -0.52])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.00, S.E. = 0.49, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.96, -2.04]; Std. beta = -0.67, 95% CI [-0.89, -0.46])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.96, S.E. = 0.59, p < .001, 95% CI [-4.13, -1.79]; Std. beta = -0.67, 95% CI [-0.93, -0.40])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
